00:21:37.660 --> 00:21:42.579
often things that we do that are really important parts of the process but that

00:21:42.579 --> 00:21:47.780
end up taking way longer than we want them to. It's often been said that the

00:21:47.780 --> 00:21:52.380
vast majority of data analysis is actually data cleaning but I find for

00:21:52.380 --> 00:22:02.380
myself my process looks a little bit more like this and I know that I'm not

00:22:02.380 --> 00:22:08.140
alone. Making things look pretty is something that this particular community

00:22:08.140 --> 00:22:15.099
is really really good at and if you're someone like Allison or Megan or Emil

00:22:15.099 --> 00:22:19.540
then you probably don't mind spending a lot of time on making things look

00:22:19.540 --> 00:22:25.939
pretty but if you're someone like me and you're not artistically talented but you

00:22:25.939 --> 00:22:30.339
still care about making things look nice then you might find yourself wishing

00:22:30.339 --> 00:22:35.859
there was an easier way. So if you're someone who finds fiddling with CSS and

00:22:35.859 --> 00:22:40.420
color palettes to be kind of tedious then I want you to know that you're not

00:22:40.420 --> 00:22:45.060
alone and I want to share with you some ways that I've been using generative AI

00:22:45.060 --> 00:22:49.819
to cut down on the amount of time that I spend on making things look pretty

00:22:49.819 --> 00:22:57.459
specifically when it comes to Cordo. I've given quite a few talks over the last

00:22:57.459 --> 00:23:03.660
few years which means I've spent quite a lot of time on making Cordo slide decks

00:23:03.660 --> 00:23:09.219
look nice. This is entirely a me problem because every time I give a new talk I

00:23:09.219 --> 00:23:13.099
want the theme to be something that people have never seen before and I also

00:23:13.140 --> 00:23:16.619
want it to be something that goes really well with the content of the slides

00:23:16.619 --> 00:23:21.979
themselves. So like this talk for example when I was picking out a theme I wanted

00:23:21.979 --> 00:23:25.619
to make sure that I picked something that was like fairly modern and minimal

00:23:25.619 --> 00:23:29.660
looking because it just would not have made sense to give a talk about AI and

00:23:29.660 --> 00:23:37.020
use Comic Sans. Now because I'm giving talks I want to make my slides publicly

00:23:37.020 --> 00:23:41.540
available to other people and I want to do this in a way that's fully

00:23:41.540 --> 00:23:46.699
reproducible where people can access not only the slides themselves but also

00:23:46.699 --> 00:23:52.380
all of the underlying files that generate them. Whenever I make changes to

00:23:52.380 --> 00:23:58.099
the content of the slides I want all of that to be version controlled and I also

00:23:58.099 --> 00:24:01.859
want the public facing version of the slides to be automatically updated as

00:24:01.859 --> 00:24:09.420
well. So this makes github pages perfect for the job and if there's anyone in the

00:24:09.459 --> 00:24:14.380
audience who's wondering if I used Cordo and github pages for this talk the

00:24:14.380 --> 00:24:20.300
answer is no because this slide deck has over 220 slides in it most of which just

00:24:20.300 --> 00:24:24.819
have images on them and if you've ever made a Cordo presentation before then

00:24:24.819 --> 00:24:29.099
you know that that would have taken way way too long but in general I do try to

00:24:29.099 --> 00:24:34.859
use Cordo and github pages for presentations. Now if you've never used

00:24:34.859 --> 00:24:40.060
github pages to host a Cordo project before then I think the best way that I

00:24:40.060 --> 00:24:45.619
can describe it is that it kind of feels like assembling a puzzle. The end result

00:24:45.619 --> 00:24:51.140
is super satisfying but you might spend hours searching for that one missing

00:24:51.140 --> 00:24:57.260
piece and the reason why I say that is because the file structure and folder

00:24:57.260 --> 00:25:01.459
structure that you need to use in order to get everything working correctly is

00:25:01.459 --> 00:25:09.300
honestly it's a little bit complicated but the good news is that once you've

00:25:09.300 --> 00:25:14.300
figured out how to successfully assemble this puzzle once you're always going to

00:25:14.300 --> 00:25:18.099
know exactly how it all fits together.

00:25:18.859 --> 00:25:24.219
Whenever you make a new Cordo theme and you post it using github pages this

00:25:24.219 --> 00:25:28.859
folder structure that you see here is going to be the exact same every single

00:25:28.859 --> 00:25:35.060
time. And if you want to make a new slide theme it's really only a handful of

00:25:35.060 --> 00:25:39.140
files that need to be modified. So you're going to need any images that you want

00:25:39.140 --> 00:25:42.660
to use for the slide backgrounds and then you're also going to need to make

00:25:42.660 --> 00:25:51.140
some modifications to the custom SCSS file. Within the custom SCSS file it's

00:25:51.140 --> 00:25:54.939
actually only a handful of lines of code that need to be modified and in

00:25:54.939 --> 00:25:58.219
particular it's really just those strings that you see highlighted there

00:25:58.219 --> 00:26:03.300
in yellow that need to be modified at all in order to create an entirely new

00:26:03.300 --> 00:26:08.420
looking theme. And that's because if we change just those strings that are

00:26:08.420 --> 00:26:12.459
highlighted in yellow then that means that we'd be changing the main font

00:26:12.459 --> 00:26:17.420
family and the color palette. And those are the styling elements that are going

00:26:17.420 --> 00:26:24.020
to make the largest most noticeable differences. Now we know that the folder

00:26:24.020 --> 00:26:29.500
structure stays the same each time and we know that all we need to do in order

00:26:29.500 --> 00:26:34.339
to create a new theme is generate some new images and make some minimal

00:26:34.339 --> 00:26:42.300
styling changes to the custom SCSS file. And we also know that generative AI is

00:26:42.300 --> 00:26:49.300
pretty good at generating images and at writing code. So we can combine all this

00:26:49.300 --> 00:26:54.219
information together and conclude that creating Cordo themes is a use case

00:26:54.219 --> 00:27:01.699
that's perfect for generative AI. So with all of these facts in mind I developed a

00:27:01.699 --> 00:27:07.699
shiny app that starts by setting up this consistent file structure and then it

00:27:07.699 --> 00:27:14.099
uses gen AI to create new images for the slide backgrounds and then the app uses

00:27:14.099 --> 00:27:19.219
chat GPT to generate styling suggestions and then update the custom

00:27:19.219 --> 00:27:26.540
SCSS file accordingly. The app looks like this and if you want to use it all you

00:27:26.540 --> 00:27:31.579
need to do is enter in a phrase for the theme and then provide your open AI API

00:27:31.579 --> 00:27:37.540
key. Once you click on the generate my theme button all of the files that are

00:27:37.540 --> 00:27:41.420
necessary for the project are going to be generated for you. You can then

00:27:41.420 --> 00:27:47.140
download those files and if you push the repo to github then the slides are

00:27:47.140 --> 00:27:51.140
going to be automatically hosted using github pages without you needing to

00:27:51.140 --> 00:28:00.219
modify any of the files. So everything's already properly configured for you. So

00:28:00.219 --> 00:28:06.579
for example I used the phrase abstract purple minimal and here's the resulting

00:28:06.579 --> 00:28:11.180
slide deck that was generated for me. And I didn't modify any of these files so

00:28:11.180 --> 00:28:15.500
this is actually what it produced. And I know it doesn't look as pretty as it

00:28:15.500 --> 00:28:20.660
would have if someone like Allison or Megan or Emil had made it but I think it

00:28:20.660 --> 00:28:27.339
looks pretty good. If you're interested in trying this app out for yourself I'm

00:28:27.339 --> 00:28:30.540
going to share the link to it in a couple of minutes but I first want to

00:28:30.540 --> 00:28:37.099
talk about how generative AI is being used here. So first the background

00:28:37.099 --> 00:28:41.979
images are generated using the image generation endpoint from the open AI API

00:28:41.979 --> 00:28:48.420
and then the prompt that's passed to the model is a concatenation of the user's

00:28:48.420 --> 00:28:57.300
input phrase and the words desktop background. And you might be wondering oh

00:28:57.300 --> 00:29:03.500
actually forgot about this slide. So if for example let's say you know that you

00:29:03.500 --> 00:29:08.099
want to create like a softer color palette for your theme and so you decide

00:29:08.099 --> 00:29:12.540
to use the phrase pastel chalk. Then what the app is going to do is it's going to

00:29:12.540 --> 00:29:17.380
take that phrase and then modify it so that the words desktop background are

00:29:17.380 --> 00:29:21.979
added and the phrase that actually gets passed to the prompt or to the image

00:29:21.979 --> 00:29:27.500
generation model is going to be pastel chalk desktop background. And you might

00:29:27.500 --> 00:29:32.380
be wondering why that's necessary and the reason is because if we don't

00:29:32.380 --> 00:29:36.020
include the words desktop background then the model is probably going to try

00:29:36.020 --> 00:29:41.859
to create a really photorealistic image like that. Whereas if we include the

00:29:41.859 --> 00:29:45.099
words desktop background then we're going to get something that looks a lot

00:29:45.099 --> 00:29:53.099
more appropriate for background images in a slide deck. From here the app then

00:29:53.099 --> 00:29:58.300
changes the opacity of the images to 20% so that if there's any text on the

00:29:58.300 --> 00:30:04.780
slides it's actually going to be visible. To generate the styling suggestions the

00:30:04.780 --> 00:30:08.780
code looks really similar to what we saw before but this time it's the chat

00:30:08.780 --> 00:30:12.660
completions endpoint that's being used. And then the prompt that gets sent to

00:30:12.660 --> 00:30:18.619
the model is super long and it says based on the user's input phrase

00:30:18.619 --> 00:30:25.540
recommend a Google font, a color palette consisting of three colors, and a Pandoc

00:30:25.540 --> 00:30:30.459
syntax highlighting theme. And then the key part of the prompt is the stuff

00:30:30.459 --> 00:30:34.420
that's at the bottom there and here I'm specifying the format that I want the

00:30:34.420 --> 00:30:40.140
results to come back in. And I'm asking for it to come back in a JSON format so

00:30:40.140 --> 00:30:42.900
that the results are going to come back in a way that I can use them

00:30:42.900 --> 00:30:49.180
programmatically instead of getting back a big long paragraph. And then finally

00:30:49.180 --> 00:30:54.479
this information is then used to populate the custom SCSS file. And if you

00:30:54.479 --> 00:30:59.319
want to see the details on how it gets populated then you can scan the QR code

00:30:59.319 --> 00:31:05.199
on the left and that's going to take you to the Shiny app on shinyapps.io. From

00:31:05.199 --> 00:31:08.280
there you can try the app out for yourself or you can take a look at the

00:31:08.280 --> 00:31:14.079
underlying code that generates it. If you want to see a video tutorial on how to

00:31:14.079 --> 00:31:17.760
use the app and how to upload everything so that it is all working with GitHub

00:31:17.760 --> 00:31:22.439
pages then I've got a video on my YouTube channel which you can access by

00:31:22.439 --> 00:31:26.239
scanning the QR code on the right. And I've also got other lots of step-by-step

00:31:26.239 --> 00:31:30.000
tutorials there as well if you're interested in learning more about how to

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:40.280
automate things in general using GitHub actions. When I was preparing for this

00:31:40.280 --> 00:31:44.640
talk and trying to decide what to include in it I messaged a lot of

00:31:44.640 --> 00:31:47.959
different people to get their perspective on what they thought might

00:31:47.959 --> 00:31:52.680
be interesting to this particular audience. A while back I was chatting

00:31:52.680 --> 00:31:57.079
with one of the other keynote speakers, Hannes, and he said that he really liked

00:31:57.079 --> 00:32:01.199
the idea of talking about practical applications of Gen AI in data science.

00:32:01.199 --> 00:32:06.359
And he also humorously shared with me that he wasn't quite sure how a cat

00:32:06.359 --> 00:32:10.719
picture generator could ever come in handy to someone who works with data. And

00:32:10.719 --> 00:32:16.920
when I saw that message I thought to myself, yeah you know what that's totally

00:32:16.920 --> 00:32:22.439
fair. There's definitely not a ton of obvious ways to use a cat picture

00:32:22.439 --> 00:32:28.199
generator as a data scientist and if I'm being completely honest the only way

00:32:28.199 --> 00:32:33.560
that I'd ever seen image generators being used in my everyday life was in a

00:32:33.560 --> 00:32:40.040
group chat at my workplace for our R and Python user group or R pug for short.

00:32:40.040 --> 00:32:44.760
One of my colleagues Jude would regularly send these hilarious AI

00:32:44.760 --> 00:32:49.280
generated images of pugs and everyone in the chat would have a great time

00:32:49.280 --> 00:32:55.079
trying to find everything that was wrong and broken with the images. And while

00:32:55.079 --> 00:33:01.520
this is a great use case but definitely improved morale, Hannes' message did make

00:33:01.520 --> 00:33:07.479
me wonder, is there a more practical way for people who work with data to use a

00:33:07.479 --> 00:33:13.160
cat picture generator? So I thought about it and I want to share with you an

00:33:13.160 --> 00:33:18.359
example of exactly how a cat picture generator might come in handy to this

00:33:18.359 --> 00:33:24.439
audience. So imagine you've just created an awesome new R package and you want to

00:33:24.439 --> 00:33:30.239
make a hex sticker which means you need a logo to represent the package. And for

00:33:30.239 --> 00:33:34.560
the sake of this discussion let's say that this package just so happens to be

00:33:34.560 --> 00:33:41.839
themed around cats. If you want to make a logo for a package then you're probably

00:33:42.040 --> 00:33:46.280
looking for an image that's got a transparent background and that can be

00:33:46.280 --> 00:33:53.280
scaled fairly easily without becoming too pixelated. There's now text to SVG

00:33:53.280 --> 00:33:58.119
generators that are perfect for exactly this. You just enter in a phrase and then

00:33:58.119 --> 00:34:03.640
an editable vector graphic is created for you. There's a ton of different

00:34:03.640 --> 00:34:09.159
services that offer this but if you're looking for a free option then ReCraft

00:34:09.280 --> 00:34:15.120
AI might be a great solution for you. Super easy to get started. You just enter

00:34:15.120 --> 00:34:20.800
a prompt and then you specify a few options. You can set the height and width

00:34:20.800 --> 00:34:28.360
ratio. You can optionally specify a color palette. You can set how simple or how

00:34:28.360 --> 00:34:33.280
detailed you want the image to be. And then you can choose from a ton of

00:34:33.399 --> 00:34:42.360
different art styles. And when I say a ton I mean a ton. I only put a few on

00:34:42.360 --> 00:34:47.199
this slide but ReCraft AI has over 20 different styles for generating vector

00:34:47.199 --> 00:34:52.520
images. Some of the styles are definitely better suited than others depending on

00:34:52.520 --> 00:34:55.600
what you're trying to use the image for. And I find that if you're trying to make

00:34:55.600 --> 00:35:02.000
a hex sticker then the cartoon style works pretty well. And just

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:07.000
like with other image generators you can do things like fine-tune or generate

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:12.080
variations. And then because the image that's been created is a vector graphic

00:35:12.080 --> 00:35:19.120
rather than a raster image you can also easily change any of the colors. Once

00:35:19.120 --> 00:35:22.159
you've got an image that you're happy with you can easily turn it into a hex

00:35:22.159 --> 00:35:28.360
sticker design. ReCraft AI also has a lot of other really cool features too

00:35:28.479 --> 00:35:33.159
including the ability to generate mock-ups which is awesome if you want to

00:35:33.159 --> 00:35:39.560
see what something's going to look like before you order a bunch of them. Next I

00:35:39.560 --> 00:35:44.399
want to talk about two tools that make teaching and communicating about data a

00:35:44.399 --> 00:35:51.820
little bit easier. The first is a tool called Scribe and Scribe allows you to

00:35:51.820 --> 00:35:56.080
automatically create step-by-step tutorials without needing to copy paste

00:35:56.080 --> 00:36:02.800
screenshots or record any videos. This is super helpful if you want to teach

00:36:02.800 --> 00:36:09.520
someone how to do a programming task. As a simple example let's say I want to

00:36:09.520 --> 00:36:15.120
show someone how to make a new R project using Posit Cloud. So first I would start

00:36:15.120 --> 00:36:18.760
the capture using the Scribe Chrome extension and then Scribe is going to

00:36:18.760 --> 00:36:22.520
start automatically writing numbered instructions based on what I'm doing in

00:36:22.520 --> 00:36:28.919
the capture. Anytime I click somewhere or type something the screenshot is going

00:36:28.919 --> 00:36:33.840
to be automatically generated for me and then the location where I've typed or

00:36:33.840 --> 00:36:39.879
clicked is going to be highlighted in orange. If I don't like the way that any

00:36:39.879 --> 00:36:44.679
of the descriptions have been written I can click on the instruction to modify

00:36:44.679 --> 00:36:52.679
what it says. Once the capture is stopped you can use Gen AI to create a

00:36:52.679 --> 00:36:57.040
title and a description for the tutorial again both of which can be modified if

00:36:57.040 --> 00:37:02.840
you don't like them. Once you're happy with the tutorial you can share it for

00:37:02.840 --> 00:37:09.120
free with others either by a direct link or by email or you can embed it as an

00:37:09.120 --> 00:37:16.159
iframe for example in a quarter website. Now using the Scribe Chrome extension is

00:37:16.159 --> 00:37:21.479
free but there's also a pro subscription available which gives you access to

00:37:21.479 --> 00:37:26.239
things like the desktop version of Scribe and the desktop version is awesome

00:37:26.239 --> 00:37:30.719
if you've got something that you want to show someone how to do using an IDE that

00:37:30.719 --> 00:37:36.600
you only have installed locally on your machine. The pro subscription also comes

00:37:36.639 --> 00:37:41.760
with the ability to export in a variety of really useful formats including

00:37:41.760 --> 00:37:49.199
Markdown. The last tool that I want to talk about that I find really helpful

00:37:49.199 --> 00:37:55.560
for teaching data science is called Descript and this is honestly probably

00:37:55.560 --> 00:38:00.679
one of the coolest things I have ever used. I've used Descript to edit every

00:38:00.679 --> 00:38:04.800
single YouTube video that I've made in the last three years and this has saved

00:38:04.800 --> 00:38:12.600
me countless hours of video editing and that's because if you use Descript you

00:38:12.600 --> 00:38:19.959
can edit videos or podcasts as if you're editing a Word document. So you just

00:38:19.959 --> 00:38:24.439
upload the video or audio file into Descript and then it's going to be

00:38:24.439 --> 00:38:29.239
transcribed for you. Transcription is available in over 20 different languages

00:38:29.239 --> 00:38:35.479
and it's really impressive, impressively accurate, sorry, even for technical words

00:38:35.479 --> 00:38:42.639
and phrases. Once the transcript is ready you can edit the transcript in order to

