or what context you're using gen AI in, this guide has a lot of really useful

00:42:32.280 --> 00:42:37.280
tips in it. You can find the guide at the link at the bottom but that link is

00:42:37.280 --> 00:42:41.360
super long so it's definitely easiest if you just Google guide on the use of

00:42:41.360 --> 00:42:44.560
generative AI and then click on the link that's from the government of

00:42:44.560 --> 00:42:52.080
Canada. This guide is super detailed but they've also developed a really

00:42:52.080 --> 00:42:57.919
convenient acronym that highlights the key principles. The acronym is FASTER and

00:42:57.919 --> 00:43:08.679
it stands for fair, accountable, secure, transparent, educated, and relevant. FAIR

00:43:08.679 --> 00:43:13.800
means ensuring that outputs are accessible, inclusive, and comply with

00:43:13.800 --> 00:43:20.439
human rights. Many of these models have used publicly available data from the

00:43:20.439 --> 00:43:24.840
internet as part of their training data which means that these models have the

00:43:24.840 --> 00:43:29.840
potential to produce outputs that amplify historical biases and stereotypes

00:43:29.840 --> 00:43:33.760
and other types of harmful information. So it's really important to always

00:43:33.959 --> 00:43:39.360
manually review outputs and remove anything that's biased, non-inclusive, or

00:43:39.360 --> 00:43:46.479
discriminatory. Gen AI should never be used to make decisions about an

00:43:46.479 --> 00:43:51.919
individual that could impact them materially or legally or lead to a

00:43:51.919 --> 00:43:59.520
discrimination in services. Doing this could violate human rights but it's also

00:43:59.639 --> 00:44:04.479
against the terms of service for most of the popular tools. So for example OpenAI

00:44:04.479 --> 00:44:10.040
has a policy that prohibits its users from using the models to make decisions

00:44:10.040 --> 00:44:14.959
about an individual related to things like credit and housing and employment.

00:44:14.959 --> 00:44:20.479
And then Google's also got a Gen AI prohibited use policy which contains

00:44:20.479 --> 00:44:28.000
some pretty similar terms. Accountable means ensuring that outputs are accurate,

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:35.439
legal, and ethical. To ensure that outputs are accurate they should always

00:44:35.439 --> 00:44:42.639
be manually reviewed by a human to make sure that it's factually correct. Large

00:44:42.639 --> 00:44:47.439
language models shouldn't be used as search engines and they also shouldn't

00:44:47.439 --> 00:44:53.000
be used for tasks that you're not already somewhat skilled in yourself. So

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:57.760
for example if I'm using Gen AI to help me out with a programming task the key

00:44:57.760 --> 00:45:03.199
word there is always help. I'm asking the model to help me out with something

00:45:03.199 --> 00:45:07.879
that I already know how to do myself and I'm asking it to use packages that I

00:45:07.879 --> 00:45:13.439
either already know and use or that I've got the documentation for opened up side

00:45:13.439 --> 00:45:17.800
by side. And this way I can actually verify that what's being produced makes

00:45:17.800 --> 00:45:25.919
sense, follows best practices, and uses a style that other people actually use.

00:45:26.560 --> 00:45:32.719
Keeping track of legalities isn't always easy if you're not a lawyer. So consult

00:45:32.719 --> 00:45:38.560
your organization's legal department if you have one. If you don't have one try

00:45:38.560 --> 00:45:43.360
your best to stay up-to-date on policy related to AI regulation however you can.

00:45:43.360 --> 00:45:48.360
And at a bare minimum make sure you've read the terms of service for any tools

00:45:48.399 --> 00:45:57.399
that you're using and ensure that your usage is compliant. Make an effort to

00:45:57.399 --> 00:46:01.879
determine whether or not the methods used to obtain the training data were

00:46:01.879 --> 00:46:09.600
legal and ethical and you can lower your risk of copyright issues by only using

00:46:09.600 --> 00:46:15.120
Gen AI for tasks that are less likely to include copyright protected information.

00:46:15.120 --> 00:46:20.520
So for example that means that you can use it to do things like edit or improve

00:46:20.520 --> 00:46:24.800
content that you wrote yourself rather than generating content completely from

00:46:24.800 --> 00:46:32.639
scratch. Secure means ensuring that personal information and privacy are

00:46:32.639 --> 00:46:37.719
protected at all times. Never enter sensitive or personal information and

00:46:37.719 --> 00:46:44.560
always abstract away as much as you possibly can. You should use synthetic

00:46:44.639 --> 00:46:50.879
data where possible or you can even go a step further and just change all the

00:46:50.879 --> 00:46:55.320
variable names in your prompt. So take the prompt that you actually want to ask

00:46:55.320 --> 00:47:00.360
and then replace all the variables with more generic names and then just change

00:47:00.360 --> 00:47:05.919
everything back after the fact. You should also make sure that you've

00:47:05.919 --> 00:47:10.840
actually read the terms of service in full and that you understand whether or

00:47:10.840 --> 00:47:15.879
not your inputs are going to be used as training data or to otherwise further

00:47:15.879 --> 00:47:20.199
improve model performance in the future. Try to opt out of this feature where

00:47:20.199 --> 00:47:26.679
possible and prioritize using services that do have an opt-out option.

00:47:27.320 --> 00:47:33.280
Transparent means being upfront about how Gen AI tools are being used. So if

00:47:33.280 --> 00:47:37.439
you've used generative AI for a project then it's really important to keep a

00:47:37.479 --> 00:47:45.320
detailed record about how it was used. If you make a public-facing tool that uses

00:47:45.320 --> 00:47:51.840
Gen AI then it's extremely important to inform users of this. The way that you

00:47:51.840 --> 00:47:56.360
inform users might be different depending on the type of content. So for

00:47:56.360 --> 00:48:01.879
example if you've generated an image you might want to include a watermark or if

00:48:01.879 --> 00:48:07.000
it's content that's text-based then you might want to include a note. And then

00:48:07.080 --> 00:48:10.919
the types of information that should be incorporated into these notes includes

00:48:10.919 --> 00:48:15.919
the exact tool and the version that was used, how the tool works and why it's

00:48:15.919 --> 00:48:22.360
being used, and to what extent outputs were reviewed or modified. And all of

00:48:22.360 --> 00:48:30.000
this should be explained in a non-technical way. Educated means being

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:35.080
knowledgeable about Gen AI tools before using them. So this means understanding

00:48:35.080 --> 00:48:39.159
the strengths and limitations of different models and also understanding

00:48:39.159 --> 00:48:45.360
how to use these tools more responsibly. It also means knowing how to write

00:48:45.360 --> 00:48:51.000
effective prompts. Most of the popular tools have really great documentation

00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:55.600
that shows you how to get the best possible results for that specific model

00:48:55.600 --> 00:49:00.320
but you might also find that taking a formal course or workshop on prompt

00:49:00.320 --> 00:49:07.120
engineering is really helpful. And finally being educated about Gen AI

00:49:07.120 --> 00:49:13.679
means keeping yourself up to date on the newest advancements and best practices.

00:49:13.679 --> 00:49:17.560
Doing this can be really really challenging because this space is

00:49:17.560 --> 00:49:22.840
constantly evolving but subscribing to newsletters or participating in

00:49:22.840 --> 00:49:28.040
communities of practice is a great way to do this. There's also a ton of talks

00:49:28.040 --> 00:49:31.719
at this conference about Generative AI that I really recommend checking out

00:49:31.719 --> 00:49:39.679
including an entire session tomorrow afternoon on exactly this topic. R is the

00:49:39.679 --> 00:49:45.479
last letter in the FASTER acronym and it stands for relevant. Relevant means

